definition.value: a group of substances that bind to a receptor to change that receptor's response to stimulus.
An antagonist at the protease-activated receptor-2.

A synthetic phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue that is the 2-aminoethyl glycoside of a pseudotetrasaccharide corresponding to a repeating unit of the Streptococcus pneumoniae type 6B capsular polysaccharide.
Protein degraders tackle tough drug targets by hijacking a cell's natural system for disposing of spent or misfolded proteins
A binding protein is any protein that acts as an agent to bind two or more molecules together.
a protein complex that is active in mitochondria and functions as a riboprotein for translating mitochondrial mRNAs encoded in mtDNA
The target that the mRNA translation initiates
Any receptor modulator acting on sigma receptors.
A sigma receptor modulator that activates the sigma-2 receptor.
A N-acyl-(4E,8Z)-sphingadienine in which the N-acyl group is specified as 2-hydroxyoctadecanoyl
An organic calcium salt of (6S)-5-methyltetrahydrofolic acid.
A 2-aminomuconic acid in which the two double bonds adopt a 2Z,4E-configuration.
A 2-aminomuconic acid in which the two double bonds adopt a 2E,4Z-configuration.

An amino oligosaccharide that is an undecasaccharide derivative in which beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc has its mannosyl group substituted at positions 3 and 6 by beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man groups, while the D-GlcNAc residue at the reducing end carries two L-Fuc residues attached via alpha-(1->3)- and alpha-(1->6)-linkages.
A polyunsaturated dicarboxylic acid dianion arising from the deprotonation of the two carboxy groups of 2-aminomuconic acid.

A branched amino pentasaccharide that is beta-D-Manp-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc in which the hydroxy group at position 3 of the mannosyl group has been glycosylated by an alpha-D-mannopyranosyl residue and the N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residue carries an alpha-L-fucosyl residue via a (1->3) linkage.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the acyl group at position 1 is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl) while that at position 2 is unspecified.

A member of the class of saikosaponins that is saikogenin E substituted by a 6-deoxy-alpha-L-mannopyranosyl-(1->4)-[beta-D-glucopyranosyl-(1->6)]-beta-D-glucopyranosyl group at position 3beta. It is a natural product isolated from the traditional Chinese herb, Radix Bupleuri and exhibits anti-HBV replication activity.
An oleanane type triterpenoid saponin.

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (4S)-5,5,5-trichloro-N-methyl-N-[(3S)-4,4,4-trichloro-3-methylbutanoyl]-L-leucine with the amino group of (1S)-1-(1,3-thiazol-2-yl)ethanamine. It is a marine metabolite initially isolated from the sponge dysidea herbacea.

A triterpenoid saponin that is the 3-O-beta-glucuronide of glycyrrhetic acid. It is a metabolite of glycyrrhizin contained in licorice and potentially a causative agent in the pathogenesis of pseudoaldosteronism.
